efore 1365":"before 1365","1330":"1330","1385":"1385","1394":"1394","1382":"1382","1368":"1368","1346":"1346","1455":"1455","1345":"1345","1300":"1300","1365":"1365","1375":"1375","about 1345":"about 1345","about 1365":"about 1365","about 1375":"about 1375","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, England","York, Yorkshire, England":"York, Yorkshire, England","Europe":"Europe","England":"England","Coldred, Kent, England":"Coldred, Kent, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Horne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, Scottish, German, and Dutch: variant of   Horn  .","Norwegian: habitational name from any of several farmsteads mostly so named from the dative singular of <i>horn</i> (see   Horn  ).","Swedish: variant of   Horn  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Horn","meanings":["English, Scottish:  see  Horne  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":37,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":110,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William Horne was born about 1345, in York, Yorkshire, England, his father, Sir Hugh Horne of Derby, was 17 and his mother, Johanna Gaasbeek, was 47. He married Horne before 1365, in Europe. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in England."},"et":{"about 1345–":"umbes 1345–Surnud","1345–Male":"1345–Surnud","1346–Female":"1346–Surnud","1365–1385":"1365–1385","1375–1394":"1375–1394","1330–1368":"1330–1368","1300–Female":"1300–Surnud","before 1365":"enne 1365","1330":"1330","1385":"1385","1394":"1394","1382":"1382","1368":"1368","1346":"1346","1455":"1455","1345":"1345","1300":"1300","1365":"1365","1375":"1375","about 1345":"umbes 1345","about 1365":"umbes 1365","about 1375":"umbes 1375","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, England","York, Yorkshire, England":"York, Yorkshire, England","Europe":"Europe","England":"England","Coldred, Kent, England":"Coldred, Kent, England"},"fi":{"about 1345–":"noin 1345–Kuollut","1345–Male":"1345–Kuollut","1346–Female":"1346–Kuollut","1365–1385":"1365–1385","1375–1394":"1375–1394","1330–1368":"1330–1368","1300–Female":"1300–Kuollut","before 1365":"ennen vuotta 1365","1330":"1330","1385":"1385","1394":"1394","1382":"1382","1368":"1368","1346":"1346","1455":"1455","1345":"1345","1300":"1300","1365":"1365","1375":"1375","about 1345":"noin 1345","about 136